Can a student just show up at school with a service dog and expect the school to allow it on the spot
Cuerpo: I am not talking about an adult visitor such as a parent coming to a meeting at a school  The case I heard about was a 4 year old with autism  The parent never mentioned to the school that the 4 year old would be bringing a dog until the bus showed up to pick him up in the morning  The bus and then school refused to allow the dog that day and said that they needed documentation first  I can see many problems with a dog just showing up at school  The staff would not know how to interact with the dog or what service the dog does  In the case of a young child or a person with a disability that needs adult supervision there needs to be a responsible adult familiar with the child and dog present at all times  There could be another student who should not be in  the same class due to a disability such as an allergy or phobia  They would need to arrange classes to accommodate both students or possibly arrange to introduce the other students to the dog  In a school setting can the school require a service dog be stipulated in a 504 plan or IEP   This would just be like a student with asthma cant just bring an undocumented inhaler to school to carry with them  Schools require medical documentation for that  Or a student with a dietary issue requiring frequent snacking during the day cant just start eating in class without prior documentation  Or a student who has difficulty walking cant just use an elevator for staff only without documentation etcyes but the documentation could be brought when the student shows up on the 1st day  but does the school really need and are the legally entitled to require it to be listed in a 504 plan or iepactual SERVICE dogs have the same rights whether it is a psychiatric service dog or a physical need service dog  Emotional Support dogs dont
